Section 1:
1 L.D. 530
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 JUDICIARY
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 349, L.D. 530, “An Act Regarding
10 Occupational Licensing Reform”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'An Act to Eliminate a Rebuttable Presumption Against the Admission of Certain
13 Applicants to the Bar'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
15 following:
16 'Sec. 1. 4 MRSA §805-A, sub-§2, ¶A, as amended by PL 1993, c. 643, §1, is
17 further amended to read:
18 A. Produces satisfactory evidence of good moral character.;
19 (1) The fact that an applicant has been convicted as an adult of a crime that is
20 punishable by imprisonment of one year or more in this State or in another state or
21 jurisdiction of the United States raises a presumption that the applicant has not met
22 this requirement. This presumption may be rebutted by proof that a lawful pardon
23 has been obtained, that extraordinary circumstances surrounded the commission of
24 the crime or that a reasonable amount of time has passed since the applicant's
25 conviction and completion of sentence and there is evidence of complete
26 rehabilitation based on the applicant's subsequent history.
27 (2) Nothing in subparagraph (1) precludes the board or the Supreme Judicial Court
28 from considering a conviction as a basis for disqualification under this paragraph;'
29 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
30 number to read consecutively.
31 SUMMARY
3322 This amendment, which is the majority report of the committee, replaces the bill, which
3333 is a concept draft, and changes the title. Under current law, there is a rebuttable
3344 presumption that an applicant for admission to the bar who has been convicted as an adult
Page 1 - 132LR2182(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 349, L.D. 530
315 of a crime punishable by at least one year of imprisonment does not have the good moral
326 character required for admission to the bar. This amendment eliminates that rebuttable
337 presumption.
Page 2 - 132LR2182(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
